Good morning Zelda, I hope you are doing well. One of a few things could be happening. 1.) If you are in editing mode, which means you clicked Edit Order and you are viewing your card- there will be error messages saying that there are zero availability because there is no more left of that item to add to your order. Whatever you had on your order before starting to edit the order is secured but the error message is saying that there is no more of this item available to add more of. 2.) If you did not hit save, which I see that you said you did- then you could have lost of the items. Previously, the old system held in the carts for 24 hours, but that is no longer the case. 3.) The last instance is that throughout the day, our warehouse team members are continuously doing quality checks. If for any reason produce fails that quality check or the warehouse team deems it as not being able to make it (quality wise) to the date it's supposed to be delivered it can be taken off of your order. I am looking at your order and I do see eggplant, potatoes, cucumbers and squash on your orders. "D" thanks so much for explaining. I was excited for a very brief moment and then it just disappeared with the produce. Oh well maybe next month. On Jun 13, 2023, at PM, DH wrote: No problem, I apologize that that happened. qm: (46 kB) Good afternoon, Thank you for reaching out about the expiration dates on your product. Unfortunately, we cannot provide specific expiration dates for these items. When a product is labeled as "assorted," it means it is a compilation of dozens of different products under that category that have been donated. These items are sorted by our volunteer teams or donated in bulk. While our volunteers are instructed not to include expired foods, items that are past their "best by" or "sell by" dates are considered acceptable for consumption and may still be included. We encourage all partners receiving these donated cases to be aware of this and to use the Food Coding Guide created by our Food Resources team and Nutrition Department. Additionally, we recommend using your knowledge of food safety and your senses (sight, smell, and texture) to determine if the food is in good condition. I apologize for not being able to provide further guidance on this matter. The nature of donated products, especially assorted bins, makes it difficult to pinpoint a specific expiration date for a mix of different items. Thank you, "D"

!Outlook-A picture .png|thumbnail! Good afternoon, Grace, I hope you are doing well. I wanted to bring this matter to Austin and discuss it with her. I understand the implications of the large orders and the concerns surrounding the removal of produce for the produce hub. When I spoke to Austin, she suggested that the first step should be to have a conversation with the partner to explain the implications of their edits to the order. They need to be mindful that they don t want to lose their produce items meant for the hub and that they should be aware of the weight of their orders when placing them. Here are two key points I discussed with Austin: 1. Currently, we do not have a formal limit for orders, so we cannot tell them what a limit would be. Operations and ERP/IT are working on measures to ensure that for large orders, the number of delivery blocks corresponds appropriately. For example, two weeks ago, Capital Christian s order required five trucks for delivery but only occupied one slot, which is unrealistic. For now, we can only ensure that Operations is aware and prepared for these situations. 2. Austin mentioned that if this situation continues to cause recurring issues and impacts the produce hub's participating sites resulting in a loss of produce we can consider locking their orders for the produce hubs and requesting that they create a separate order. However, this could complicate matters since Operations has asked us to consolidate orders for the same partner to avoid having one sales order versus two. We can explore this locking option as a last resort if recurring issues continue. I hope this clarifies the situation, and please let me know if you need any assistance in engaging with the partner. Best, "D"

Good afternoon Godwin, This year, our Food Procurement Team purchased two truckloads of turkeys, each at a cost of approximately $60 to $70 per case and were available on PartnerLink. These turkeys have been allocated to various orders and are no longer available. I reached out to my colleagues on the Food Resources Team, who informed me that we often receive donated turkeys. These donations will be provided at no cost now that the shared mainte ce fee has been waived for donated items. However, we cannot predict if and when these donations will arrive. Typically, individuals and organizations tend to donate turkeys closer to Thanksgiving, usually in the week before the holiday or during the holiday week itself. Please continue to check the menu regularly to see if turkeys are added. If we do receive them, they will be added to the menu and available to partners on a first-come, first-served basis. Regards, Godwin Binutu Good afternoon Godwin, I hope this message finds you well. Thank you for reaching out to me again regarding the turkey availability. I completely understand how important this is for your community, especially during the holidays. I want to clarify that all the turkeys we receive are available on a first come, first served basis for all our partners, just like other items on the menu. I also realize that in previous years, there was a fee associated with our donated turkeys (0.19 cents per pound). However, I m pleased to share that this fee has been waived for this fiscal year, so it s possible you may have paid in the past but you would not have to this time for the donated product. I genuinely want to ensure that you and your clients receive the support you need this holiday season. I understand how quickly these items can disappear from the menu, and I encourage you to check it daily, as we frequently add new products. Right now, we also have vegetable oil, stuffing mix, corn muffin mix, canned collard greens, and beans that might help supplement your holiday distributions. Please feel free to check the menu regularly, and if I see any additional turkeys come available, I will reach out to you. Thank you for your understanding, and know that we are here to support you and your community during this important time. Good afternoon Partner, Thank you for your inquiry about Capacity Grants. We do indeed offer Capacity Grants at Capital Area Food Bank intended to help our partners expand their operations by providing fi cial assistance to cover the cost of items like storage or a vehicle. The Capacity Grant Application is embedded in our 2024 Fall Bi-Annual Survey, which will be released to partners in the second week of October. Please note that you will need to open and fill out the survey to access the Capacity Grant Application and then submit it. Once you submit your application, it will be reviewed by your Regional Team for consideration. Thank you, Customer Relations Please also reach out to your Regional Team Members to learn more about external grant opportunities that may be available for support.

Good morning, I hope this message finds you well! I wanted to reach out regarding your request. I have combined everything for your order tomorrow into SO185606. Going forward, please contact us by phone or email before creating multiple orders. The reason we do not combine orders is that, systematically, it can cause issues. Please let me know if you need any other information. Thank you Good afternoon accepts donations with items past their best by and sell by dates. The best by date is an indicator of the quality of a product but is not a safety date. The sell by date is for inventory management and tells the store for how long to display the product for sale. The product can still be consumed after this date. It's important to note that many of our donated products will be past these dates, but they are not expired and are still safe for consumption. We have food coding guides that partners can print and reference during distributions. When available, they can be ordered in English and Spanish from our Nutrition Education Department. The dates on some products may cause concerns for partners and their clients, but we urge you all to differentiate between the different dates on products, use the food coding guide as a reference, and also use your best judgment as well as your food safety knowledge. If you have a product that is not of the right consistency, has an odor, or you believe to be not okay, please let us know and discard the item immediately. As we increase our donations, we may encounter some challenges, but please work with us and continue to provide us with feedback. Additionally, if you ever have an issue with fresh produce, please include photos of the items so that we can forward them to our Operations and Food Resourcing Departments for their knowledge. We appreciate your partnership with us in this. For Nutrition Materials including the Food Coding Guide, please email: "D"

Good afternoon, Thank you for contacting our Customer Service. I'd be happy to assist you with your query. Our system applies grants on a per-line-item basis, meaning only one grant can be applied to each line item. In your past couple of orders, you have had line items with high numbers ranging from $250 to $2,653.30. The system is going to use the grant that has enough available funds which might not be the one with the closest expiration date. Please see below: You have three grants: 1-G $3,000 (Expires 1^st^) SO136067 used $890.00 SO122558 used $812.60 Remaining Balance: $514.98 1-H $2,378 (Expires 2^nd^) SO146902 used $762.58 SO142621 used $1,498.84 Remaining Balance: $116.58 1-I $6,564 (Expires 3^rd^) SO157471 (your most recent order) was placed and totaled in $854.20, the only grant that could cover the entirety of this line item for the chicken was your 1-I grant. If the system pulled from either of your other two grants, it would not cover the total cost of the chicken. I hope this clarifies the situation. Just so you are aware, working doesn't automatically mean someone is able-bodied. "Able-bodied" typically refers to a person who has no physical disabilities and can perform tasks without any limitations caused by a disability. qm: Hi for assistance. We will reply as soon as possible. Thank you, Customer Relations Capital Area Food Bank Good afternoon, Thank you for contacting customer support. I am looking into the dates for your previous orders to confirm that they are safe to eat. As a reference, feel free to use our Food Coding Guide (attached) as a resource when navigating different dates. I will follow up with you as soon as I get updates regarding the products you asked about. Hi Andrea, I hope you are doing well. I wanted to talk to you about the ticket you submitted. I apologize for the delay. One of my team members brought up your concerns regarding some items you received from us. After discussing your concerns about the salad dressing with my management and the Food Sourcing Team responsible for all the food that comes into the Food Bank, here are some points I wanted to share with you. Regarding the salad dressing, our Food Resourcing Team does not have a specific recommendation for shelf-stable milk or salad dressing in our Food Coding Guide. We suggest following the USDA's recommendation regarding this product specifically and apologize for not being able to provide further insight. Partners and clients should use their eyes, noses, and, taste buds to determine if a food is spoiled and therefore unsafe to eat. Of course, if a product is showing any signs of spoilage such as rot, mold, foul odor, etc., we will accept a return. I have brought this issue to management's attention, and I agree that our Food Coding Guide needs improvement. I will raise this with our leadership for further review. In response to your second point, I acknowledge the importance of best-by dates for our partners and their clients. However, our team faces challenges in obtaining these dates for donated products. One challenge arises during packing events when volunteers check and pack donated items into cases labeled as assorted on the menu. These assorted cases contain items from various donors and are packed without specific best-by date information for each individual product. Another challenge occurs when we receive donated products in different case lots-with different dates, making it difficult to provide accurate best-by dates to our partners. We don't know what case lot your order is going to be pulled from until its pulled the day before or two before its delivered or picked up. Although we practice FIFO (first in, first out) inventory management, the dynamic nature of our inventory makes it challenging to predict best-by dates with certainty. As our inventory of donated products increases, we are committed to improving our processes to provide partners with the information they need to make informed decisions. We are continuously seeking ways to improve our processes, and I encourage partners to participate in the upcoming Partner meetings in July to address any questions or recommendations regarding product dates. Thank you for bringing these concerns to our attention. Warm regards, "D"

Hi Andrea, I spoke to the Regional Coordinators and below is the itnel that they had to share about this topic: Partners cannot require clients to volunteer in exchange for food. This policy must be clearly communicated between both parties (partner site and volunteer). However, if a volunteer needs food and wishes to continue volunteering, partners have the option to take them on as clients as well. Since you are using Service Insights, the partners will need to create a client profile for the volunteer in the same manner as they do for all clients. Volunteers have the same access to food as clients. Therefore, if the partner has zip code or income restrictions, the volunteer must meet the same qualifications as clients do. Let me know if you need any further questions! "D" "D", Thank you very much for the information. Good afternoon, Thank you for reaching out to Customer Relations. I appreciate your inquiry. We offer a variety of fruits and vegetables on our menu throughout the week, but the selection can vary depending on seasonal availability. During the winter months, for example, we typically have fewer options compared to the summer when a wider variety of produce is available. In recent weeks, the fruits and vegetables available have primarily included potatoes, apples, and carrots. Due to producelimitations placed on agencies, our Food Resources Team is working to bring in more produce items in case lot instead of large bins and full pallets, but this remains an ongoing challenge. Currently, all produce items must be ordered through PartnerLink, as there are no plans to reopen the agency mart for direct pickups. I have two suggestions to enhance your experience in this situation. First, you can place orders up to 10 days in advance of your scheduled pickup and delivery date. I recommend placing your order as soon as the calendar opens and frequently checking PartnerLink for available produce. You can edit and add to your order until it locks for fulfillment, which is three business days prior to the shipment date. This flexibility allows you to include any additional items you may find during that 10-day window. Another option is to explore our TEFAP program, a government-subsidized initiative through which participating partners can access additional items to supplement their regular orders. Please note that this program has specific requirements and is managed by the TEFAP team. For more information, you can reach out to Zaynab, the DC TEFAP coordinator: Thank you! Best regards, "D"

Sent from [Mail| for Windows From: Hi Marian, I reached out to our food resourcing team, and they said they were made aware of this by other partners. Our team has reached out to Feeding America to see if they could provide assistance on obtain a recipe for this item. My colleague said she would get back to me, as soon as she heard back from them. Our apologies about this. DH Hi Marian, I am so sorry for the delay. Feeding America got back to our food resourcing team about the biscuits. Please see below: Rolled Biscuits: Yield 6-8 biscuits. 1 pkg Jack & the Beanstalk Buttermilk Biscuit Mix, 1/2 cup water, preheat oven to 450 degrees F. Blend biscuit mix and water to a soft dough. Turn dough onto lightly floured surface, knead several times. Pat or roll dough 1/2 inch thick. Cut with 2 inch floured cutter and place on ungreased baking sheet. Bake about 10 minutes. Drop Biscuits: Follow recipe above except do not knead. Drop by spoonful onto ungreased baking sheet. Bake 10-12 minutes. Do not eat raw batter, dough or mix. Corn Muffins: Yield 6 - 8 muffins depending on size. 1 pkg. Jack & the Beanstalk Cornbread Mix and Corn muffin mix. 1 egg. 1/3 cup milk. Preheat oven to 400 degrees F. Grease muffin pan or use paper baking cups. Blend ingredients. Batter will be slightly lumpy. (for maximum crown on muffins let batter rest for 3 or 4 minutes, stir lightly before filling cups.) Fill muffin cups 2/3 full. Bake 15 - 20 minutes or until golden brown. Thank you for your patience. DH

Hi for assistance. We will reply as soon as possible. Thank you, Customer Relations Capital Area Food Bank Good morning, Thank you for your questions about the limited items on the menu. While I don't have a general answer, there are several factors at play. Firstly, at certain times of the year, we have constraints on our receiving calendar, which leads to fewer inventory trucks due to scheduling conflicts. Currently, we are facing this situation as we were closed for Juneteenth, went through our bi-annual inventory last week, and will also be closed for the July 4th observance next week. Additionally, as we prepare for our move back to home building in the Virginia region, there may be a slight shift in the amount of products as we transition inventory from one location to another. This means we have been and will continue to receive fewer trucks than usual and are trying to schedule loads that fit within this restricted schedule. Moreover, while donations vary, we are actively working to increase the amount of donated food we receive and make it available through our Partner Direct Program and the menu. This issue will be discussed in an upcoming in-person partner meeting in July, giving partners the opportunity to hear from our leadership and our Food Resourcing Team, who are responsible for sourcing all the food on the menu, both donated and purchased. Let me know if you have any further questions or concerns. Thanks, "D"

qm: Good morning Jeanette, I hope you re doing well today. I was very concerned to hear about the issues you ve encountered with mice droppings and the presence of mice near the food you received from us. Please know that I am genuinely sorry for this distressing experience, and I want to extend my heartfelt apologies on behalf of Capital Area Food Bank and our Customer Service and Operations Team. This morning, I forwarded the information you provided in your ticket, along with your photos, to our Director of Operations. She is taking this matter very seriously and has scheduled a meeting with her team to ensure we find a prompt and effective resolution. They will be focusing on maintaining cleanliness and ensuring rodent protection in our facilities, as well as inspecting our warehouse products, particularly those in question, to ensure they are removed if necessary. I want to support you through this situation. Could you please let me know which specific products you needed to be disposed of due to the potential rodent issue, aside from the bins of cereal? I understand how disruptive this can be to your food distribution efforts, and I truly empathize with the challenges it presents in providing safe and healthy food to the community you serve. I will also reach out to my supervisor to discuss possible compensation for the inconvenience caused by this situation, as we value your partnership and want to make things right. Thank you for your understanding, and once again, I m truly sorry for the trouble this has caused. We are committed to resolving this matter as quickly as possible. Best wishes, "D" "D", Thank you so much for your prompt response and for addressing this matter with great regard. We look forward to hearing back from your side the resolution made from your side so this situation can be avoided. When it comes to your questions around damages and pain points that we encounter to intervene quickly here are some of the damages it costs my operations: We disregard about 50 Rx Boxes that were packed and ready for distribution to our Food as Medicine Program (this is worth $25 each box) We halted our packing operations (2 days' worth) and had caused me loss of 500 Rx Boxes that should have been packed last week. Instead, we used the time to do a deep cleaning to ensure all our 800 Rx Boxes are safe. We also use two additional days of work to contain and capture the three mice and safely throw the 2 bins of assorted cereals out of our building premises (into a landfill). (Note: I personally set aside my own list of tasks to help my team do this work for two days and also recruit four people to assist us with this problem) I hope this helps you and your organization understand how this type of matters can cause a small organization like ours not only inconvenience/stress but lost of products/investment/productivity for some of our programs outside our Food Pantry operations. ---- I hope this message finds you well. I wanted to reach out personally to follow up on the recent incident and to express my sincere apologies for any disruption it may have caused you. I have escalated this matter to our Operations Director, and I want you to know that we have a new leader in Operations who is dedicated to ensuring we serve our partners with the utmost care and precision. She is committed to making improvements and has assured me that we are taking significant steps to prevent such situations from occurring in the future. Some of the measures we re implementing include: 1. Continuing our routine pest control efforts. 2. Collaborating with our pest control company, which visited our facility on Monday to conduct additional work beyond our normal mainte ce. 3. Strengthening our inspection processes to ensure that all pullers, drivers, and inspectors thoroughly check every order once it's staged. 4. Focusing on the quality of products going out to our partners. 5. Preparing for the warmer months ahead to maintain a rodent-free and clean environment for the food we deliver. I truly empathize with the impact this situation may have had on your operations, and I want to assure you that we are committed to providing a better service moving forward. Please know that we value your partnership and appreciate your understanding during this time. As a gesture of goodwill, we would like to waive the delivery fees for both your recent order and your upcoming order on March 3rd. If you have any questions or concerns, please don t hesitate to reach out. Your feedback is important to us, and we re here to help. Thank you for your understanding. Warm regards, "D" Thanks! ---- ,"content":[

Thank you for your inquiry on s Feature on PartnerLink. We encouraged all partners to attend one of the four trainings that we hosted between August and September to ensure that everyone was well-equipped to utilize this feature effectively. This feature is crucial for maintaining accurate information about your agency's operating hours, which in turn updates our [Get Help Map| on the website. The Get Help Map is a tool that clients use to locate nearby CAFB Partners, so it's essential to have the correct hours displayed. If you were unable to attend the trainings, don't worry. There are alternative options available, such as accessing the resource on PartnerLink under the Partner Resources tab, or signing up for [Customer Relations Office Hours| held every Wednesday from 10am-11am. Please note that due to the nature of the training, there are no recordings or slides available, as it involved a live demo and Q&A session. While partners are not being reprimanded for not attending a training, it's important to highlight that starting October 1st, partners who have not updated or confirmed their hours will see a banner prompting them to do so before placing an order. You will need to take this action to proceed with making an order. If your hours have not changed, simply verify them by accessing the Agency Overview section after clicking your agency name on PartnerLink. If changes are necessary, please update them accordingly. For further assistance, please contact us at So I went and clicked verify. Are we good now? Thanks, Jeff Yes, you are good. In the future, when you receive requests for updates, your account is not locked; it is simply asking for you to verify your information before you can proceed with placing an order. Have a great day! "D"

Good morning, Luanne, Happy New Year! I hope you had a great holiday. I have attached our Inclement Weather Policy below. In the event that it snows, we will wait for information from our leadership, including the Head of Operations, to determine if we will have a formal delay or closure - we do not follow the government s decisions regarding weather. For example, if we announce a 2-hour delay, all delivery and pickup windows will be pushed back accordingly. This means that if you had an 8 AM - 10 AM delivery, it will now be scheduled for 10 AM - 12 PM. If we face a complete closure due to the weather, there will be no deliveries or pickups. On such days, the Customer Relations team will be available to reschedule deliveries and reach out to all partners regarding their orders. Additionally, please keep in mind that depending on the amount of snow, there may be impacts on the days following the snowfall. If we do have a closure, we will do our best to accommodate our partners' schedules while ensuring that orders are not affected the following day. I hope this helps! Please let me know if you need any further information. Best, "D" you, "D"! Luanne

Good morning Mitilde, I hope you are doing well. Thank you for sharing your feedback with us; it is very valuable. I will follow up with the Transportation Leadership Team to address the way the drivers communicate with partners about this issue. To provide some context, there are two main reasons why drivers may not take pallets when dropping off food during a delivery. Firstly, they may have food for an immediate order or need to pick up food from another site for the warehouse, which means they cannot have food and pallets on the truck at the same time due to food safety (Pallets are often leftoutside- on the ground, possibly in the rain, and are often dirty) and consideration for our partners. Secondly, our drivers may be on tight schedules and do not have the time for a pallet pickup due to their busy delivery schedules, especially during the busy season. There is no reason why a driver could not explain this to you at the time, and I will ensure that this information is communicated to them. I apologize for your experience. Thank you, "D" I spoke with the Transportation Supervisor, and she mentioned that she received feedback about the pallets not being stacked properly and having trash around them. She has scheduled a pallet pickup for tomorrow. Please make sure that the pallets are stacked together to allow the equipment to pick them up easily, there is no debris around them, and they are placed on concrete, not on grass. Thank you! qm: This is how the pallets were placed. We can t stack them any higher, so we have to put them to the side due to our limited space. Good morning, Alexis, I hope this message finds you well, and Happy New Year! Thank you for providing this important information; it is definitely something we need to note. To give you some background, partners have been charged delivery fees for orders that include a mix of TEFAP products and other donated or purchased items for some time. As stated in our SMART Shopping Policy, orders that contain only TEFAP products do not incur a delivery fee. However, orders that mix TEFAP with purchased or donated products do have a delivery fee associated with them. I do not have the ability to remove delivery fees from all orders, as these fees are automatically added when partners place their orders. I believe we will need to submit an ERP ticket to stop this charge permanently, as it is an automated process. To clarify what the ticket would entail: Are we asking for no delivery fees to be applied to any orders containing any TEFAP items for al regions? Additionally, will we need to issue refunds for past orders that were charged delivery fees due to the mix of TEFAP and other products? I anticipate that partners will inquire about previous orders that included these fees as we proceed with this change and it also may be a good idea to plan for a formal communication to TEFAP partners since this is a change in poliy that we have previously stated to them. Is there a deadline for when this needs to be implemented? I understand that it should be done as soon as possible, but any changes/refunds to delivery fees are always approved by Austin, who is currently out until January 9th. Thank you for bringing this matter back to our attention again, hope to resolve this as soon as possible! Best, "D" Hey "D", happy new year and thanks for your response! Yes, we re asking for no delivery fees to be applied to any orders containing any TEFAP items for al regions. But, I don t think we need to issue refunds or change this immediately. I can flag this to Austin for when she returns and circle back to you. Agreed that we ll need to send out a communication, and my thought is we can word it as this will be our process going forward. Closing this ticket as this issue is currently being handled by Alexis and Austin. If any further steps are taken, the associated teams will be made aware.

Thank you, Customer Relations Capital Area Food Bank Good afternoon, Thank you for contacting customer support. While we do not have many ready-to-eat items on our menu at the moment, we are looking into what may be useful to order for the future. Can you please let me know specific or approximate volumes that you would like of each item? We will work on trying to build a more mixed menu to accommodate what your organization needs. Thank you, distribute approximately 180 - 220 bags each week. Our bags contain the following items: Bottled water, milk shelf stable 8oz, juice box 6-10oz, applesauce cup 4oz, tuna pouch 2oz, package of peanut butter cracker (lance)/ chips 1oz bags variety, package of cookies/granola bar, cereal in prepackaged bowl, 2 saltine packs ( 2 cracker in each pack). I hope this helps. When I order it is based on need and the amount of storage space we have. Usually it is 50-60 cases of milk( 27 boxes per case), 12-18 cases of applesauce(96 cups per case), pallet or water ( 48 cases of 24 bottles per case). These items usually last 2- 3months. Items we get from Sckenck Foods include: 14 prepackaged cereal bowls (96 per case), 8 peanut butter cracker (12 8packs per case) , 20-30 juice boxes (motts 36 per case), 6 saltines (500 2pk) 8 cookies (120 pks per case). Trips to BJ's, Costco , Walmart and Amazon provide some of the above and also the 50 tuna (10-12 2oz pouches per box). Sometimes we even get Vienna sausages. Granted none of this is considered healthy but it is convenient and ready to eat. We also distribute canned goods to those who have a place to cook ( about 6-15) a week. Let me know if you have any questions or need anything else. ---- Thank you for the insight. Our Food Resourcing team will be using this information to incorporate more Ready-To-Eat products in the near future. As for now I do not see us having any of the products you mentioned coming in on our schedule. That may change and I encourage you to keep checking our menu on Partnerlink for updates.

qm: Dr. Head, We appreciate the wonderful service you provide to your community and your partnership with CAFB for the last 15 years. Different programs within CAFB have different rules and regulations. TEFAP falls under the rules and regulations of MD DHS, collection of SDI forms is one of the requirements set forth by them not by myself or by CAFB. I completely understand that the work that you and all your volunteers do is hard and exhausting work. We also understand that not everyone is able to, qualifies for, or feels comfortable completing the SDI form. This is why we do always recommend there be non TEFAP food set aside for those do not qualify or are unable to complete the SDI form. My goal is not to suspend New Hope and Life Church of God, it is to work with you and each partner to ensure there is compliance with regulations set forth by MD DHS, to work together when other problems arise, and to get to know each partner to the best of my ability so that I can continue to advocate for change at the state level. Regarding the monthly inventory report for the month of August, like covered in the civil rights training, regardless of whether food was distributed a report must still be submitted. In the case of no distribution, you would just need to put 0 under the household and individuals served, note any inventory you have at the time, sign and submit. I can also look at your sales order record and send you the food ordered around that time frame which may help in the completion of the report. I do want to remind you that I am out of town tomorrow Friday October 24th and Monday, October 28th. Like stated in the previous emails, what needs to be submitted on Wednesday, October 23rd is the signed corrective action plan, a summary of how you will be collecting SDI forms, and submission of the monthly inventory reports that have not yet been submitted. Submission of the reports can be through the links originally sent or if your organization completed the reports previously, they should have been sent an email copy of the report which can then be emailed to me. I appreciate your patience, understanding and the work you and you organization does for the community. Best, Lucy

Toni Gaines Our Lady of Perpetual Help Church 301-222-7285 ---- Hi Toni, Please note that even if an item is in your cart, items do not hold. There is a chance the catfish could have been purchased while you were ordering, changing the total quantity available. I believe this is what happened with you. We apologize that you were not able to purchase the catfish as our products are available on first come first serve basis. Please let me know if I can be of further assistance. qm: Hi , I'm aware that items are on a first come first serve basis. However, the items were in the cart. I saved the cart and it showed 10 items in the cart when I only ordered the 5 items available. This is when the pdf of the order did not appear for me to download. The screen had an error message instead stating the 10 items were not available, but I only ordered 5 which were available. Can we be put on a waiting list should you get more catfish? Thanks for your response. Toni Gaines We appreciate your patience as we look into this issue. Can you please confirm if this was a TEFAP product or not? , Yes, the catfish was a TEFAP product. Thanks, Toni Gaines Our Lady of Perpetual Help Church Good afternoon, We contacted the TEFAP Team and learned that we anticipate receiving a shipment of catfish between October 16th and 31st. Currently, we do not have a waitlist or a reminder system linked to our inventory to alert partners when items are back in stock. This is feedback we have received from partners and have conveyed to our Food Resourcing and Inventory Teams for consideration. If you wish to check back during that time and do not see the catfish available, we would be happy to reach out to the TEFAP team to confirm if the shipment is still expected during that period. It seems that in your original order, the product went out of stock. Our inventory is live and operates on a first-come, first-served basis as you know. At times, items may be taken by the time you start the checkout process, resulting in an error message prompting you to update your item quantities based on what's available. Additionally, there may be different lots of items with varying expiration dates. Consequently, you may have two lots of the same product arriving at different times, with one having a later expiration date than the other. Depending on the date of your order, the item may have gone out of stock for the specific case lot you selected, even though there are still some available on the menu. This occurs due to the date you chose for your order. We acknowledge that our inventory system is complex and are striving to make it more user-friendly and accessible for partners to obtain information from the website. Thank you, Customer Relations
